---
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import "../../../styles/global.css";

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  "itemListElement": [
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Guides", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/guides/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "Secondary Income Tax", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/guides/secondary-income-tax/" }
  ]
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why is the tax on my second job so high?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Tax on a second job can seem high because it is taxed at a flat rate (17.5%, 30%, 33%, or 39%) rather than the progressive scale used for your primary job. This is because the progressive brackets are already allocated to your primary income. The flat rate on secondary income approximates your marginal rate. You are not being double-taxed; the total tax across both jobs should roughly match what you would owe on your combined income."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I have to tell my employer about my second job?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "You must tell each employer your correct tax code, which means informing your secondary employer that this is not your primary job. You do not necessarily need to tell your primary employer about the second job unless your employment agreement requires it or there is a conflict of interest. However, both employers need the correct tax code to deduct the right amount of PAYE."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I get a refund if too much tax was deducted from my second job?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. If the flat rate used on your secondary income results in more tax being deducted than you actually owe based on your total income, IRD will issue a refund as part of your automatic income tax assessment after the end of the tax year (31 March). You can also apply for a tailored (special) tax code from IRD to reduce over-deductions during the year."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="Secondary Income Tax in New Zealand: Rates & When It Applies | TakeHomePay.nz"
  description="How tax works when you have two or more jobs in New Zealand. Learn about secondary tax codes, flat rates, and how to avoid overpaying or underpaying PAYE."
  canonical="/guides/secondary-income-tax/"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary to-primary-light py-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 text-center text-white">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold mb-4 text-white">Secondary Income Tax in New Zealand: Rates & When It Applies</h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-white/90">How tax works when you have more than one job, and how to choose the right tax code.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="mb-8 text-sm text-text-muted">
        <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 flex-wrap">
          <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Home</a></li>
          <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-2 before:text-border"><a href="/guides/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Guides</a></li>
          <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-2 before:text-border font-medium text-text">Secondary Income Tax</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          If you hold more than one job in New Zealand, you need to understand how secondary income tax works. Many New Zealanders work multiple jobs simultaneously, whether it is a part-time evening job alongside a full-time career, freelance or gig work on the side, or seasonal employment during busy periods. However the tax on a second job often surprises people, because it is deducted at a flat rate rather than the progressive scale used for primary employment. This guide explains why secondary tax exists, how the rates work, which tax code to use, and how to make sure you are not paying more (or less) tax than you should.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Why Secondary Tax Exists</h2>

        <p>
          New Zealand's PAYE system uses progressive tax brackets, where each portion of your income is taxed at increasing rates as you earn more. When you have a single employer, the system works smoothly, applying the correct bracket to each dollar of income. But when you have two or more employers, each employer only knows about the income they pay you. Without secondary tax codes, both employers would apply the progressive scale independently, meaning the lower tax brackets would be used twice, and you would end up paying too little tax overall.
        </p>

        <p>
          Secondary tax codes solve this problem by applying a flat withholding rate to the income from your second (and any subsequent) jobs. The flat rate approximates the marginal tax rate that would apply if the secondary income were added on top of your primary income. This ensures that roughly the right amount of tax is withheld throughout the year, avoiding a large bill from IRD at the end of the tax year.
        </p>

        <p>
          It is important to understand that secondary tax is not an additional tax. You are not being taxed twice or penalised for having two jobs. The total amount of tax you owe across all your income is exactly the same whether you have one job or five. Secondary tax codes are simply a mechanism to ensure the correct total amount is collected during the year through the PAYE system.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Secondary Tax Rates for 2025-2026</h2>

        <p>
          The secondary tax rate you use depends on your total expected annual income from all sources. Your primary employer uses the M or ME code, applying the full progressive tax scale. Each secondary employer uses one of the following flat-rate codes:
        </p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
          <table class="w-full border-collapse border border-border text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-surface-alt">
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Tax Code</th>
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Flat Rate</th>
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Total Annual Income Range</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">S</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">17.5%</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Up to $15,600</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-surface"><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">SH</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">30%</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$15,601 - $53,500</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">ST</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">33%</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$53,501 - $78,100</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-surface"><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">SA</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">33%</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$78,101 - $180,000</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">SB</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">39%</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Above $180,000</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>
          To determine the correct code, estimate your total annual income from all employment. For example, if your primary job pays $55,000 and your second job pays $10,000, your total income is $65,000. Looking at the table, this falls in the $53,501 to $78,100 range, so you would use the ST code for your second job.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Which Job Should Be the Primary One?</h2>

        <p>
          Your primary job should be the one where you earn the most income. This is the job that uses the M or ME tax code and gets the benefit of the progressive tax scale, starting with the low 10.5 percent rate on the first $15,600 of income. All other jobs use secondary tax codes.
        </p>

        <p>
          If your employment situation changes during the year, for example if you reduce hours at one job and increase them at another so that a different job becomes your main earner, you should update your tax codes accordingly. Give the new primary employer an IR330 form with the M or ME code, and give the former primary employer a new IR330 with the appropriate secondary code.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Why Does My Second Job Tax Seem So High?</h2>

        <p>
          One of the most common complaints about secondary income tax is that the take home pay from a second job seems disproportionately low. When you see 30 percent or 33 percent taken from your secondary earnings, it can feel like you are being punished for working extra hours. However, as explained above, this is not additional tax. It is simply the system trying to collect the right total amount of tax across all your income.
        </p>

        <p>
          Consider this example: Sarah earns $50,000 from her main job and $15,000 from a weekend job. Her total income is $65,000. On her main job, she pays progressive PAYE starting at 10.5 percent and going up to 30 percent. On her weekend job, she uses the ST code and pays 33 percent on all $15,000 of that income. If she only had one job paying $65,000, the tax on the top portion of her income ($53,501 to $65,000) would be 30 percent, with the remainder taxed at lower rates. The 33 percent flat rate on the secondary income slightly over-collects, and she would likely receive a small refund from IRD after the end of the tax year.
        </p>

        <p>
          The reality is that the flat rates are designed to be approximate. They will sometimes collect slightly too much and sometimes slightly too little, depending on the exact income levels. IRD reconciles everything after the tax year and adjusts accordingly.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Student Loans and Secondary Income</h2>

        <p>
          If you have a student loan, your secondary tax codes need to include the "SL" suffix. The relevant codes are SSL, SHSL, and STSL. Student loan repayments are deducted at 12 percent on all income from the secondary job, because the repayment threshold is already accounted for in your primary job's deductions. This means that every dollar earned from a secondary job with a student loan attracts 12 percent student loan repayment on top of the secondary tax rate.
        </p>

        <p>
          For example, with the SHSL code, your total deduction rate would be 30 percent secondary PAYE plus 12 percent student loan, equalling 42 percent of your secondary earnings going to deductions. Add ACC Earner's Levy (1.60 percent) and any KiwiSaver contributions, and your take home pay from the secondary job could be as low as 40 to 50 percent of your gross earnings. While this can feel discouraging, remember that these are not additional taxes; they represent the correct total tax and repayment obligations on your combined income.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Tailored Tax Codes for Multiple Jobs</h2>

        <p>
          If you find that the standard secondary tax codes consistently result in too much or too little tax being deducted, you can apply to IRD for a tailored tax code (also called a special tax code). IRD will assess your specific situation, including all your income sources and deductions, and issue a customised rate that your secondary employer should use.
        </p>

        <p>
          A tailored tax code can be particularly useful if your secondary income varies significantly throughout the year, if you have tax credits or deductions that the standard codes do not account for, or if you have multiple secondary jobs and the combined over-deduction is substantial. You can apply for a tailored tax code through your myIR account or by contacting IRD directly.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">KiwiSaver on Secondary Employment</h2>

        <p>
          If you are a KiwiSaver member, contributions are deducted from all your employment income, not just your primary job. Your secondary employer must also deduct KiwiSaver at your chosen rate (3, 4, 6, 8, or 10 percent) and make the minimum 3 percent employer contribution. This means you are building additional retirement savings from your secondary income, though it further reduces your take home pay.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you want to avoid KiwiSaver deductions on secondary employment, you would need to take a savings suspension, but this applies to all your employment, not just the secondary job. You cannot selectively opt out of KiwiSaver for one employer while remaining enrolled with another.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Gig Work and Contract Income</h2>

        <p>
          The rise of the gig economy means many New Zealanders earn secondary income through platforms like Uber, freelancing, or short-term contracts. If you are classified as an employee, the employer must deduct PAYE using the appropriate secondary tax code. However, if you are classified as a self-employed contractor, PAYE is not deducted at source, and you are responsible for managing your own tax obligations through provisional tax or the accounting income method.
        </p>

        <p>
          The distinction between employment and self-employment is important and sometimes complex. Factors that determine your status include the degree of control the engaging party has over how, when, and where you work, whether you provide your own tools and equipment, and whether you bear financial risk. If you are unsure whether your secondary income is employment or self-employment, the IRD and Employment New Zealand websites provide guidance, and you may wish to seek professional advice.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">End-of-Year Tax Reconciliation</h2>

        <p>
          After the end of each tax year (31 March), IRD reviews your total income from all sources and the total PAYE deducted across all your jobs. If the secondary tax rates resulted in too much tax being collected, you will receive a refund. If too little was collected, you will receive a bill. Most people with multiple jobs find that the secondary tax system works reasonably well, with any adjustments being relatively small.
        </p>

        <p>
          IRD typically processes these automatic assessments between May and July following the end of the tax year. If you have a refund, it is usually deposited directly into your bank account. If you owe money, IRD provides options for payment including instalment arrangements.
        </p>

        <!-- FAQ Section -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4 not-prose">
          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              Why is the tax on my second job so high?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">Tax on a second job can seem high because it is taxed at a flat rate (17.5%, 30%, 33%, or 39%) rather than the progressive scale used for your primary job. This is because the progressive brackets are already allocated to your primary income. The flat rate on secondary income approximates your marginal rate. You are not being double-taxed; the total tax across both jobs should roughly match what you would owe on your combined income.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              Do I have to tell my employer about my second job?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">You must tell each employer your correct tax code, which means informing your secondary employer that this is not your primary job. You do not necessarily need to tell your primary employer about the second job unless your employment agreement requires it or there is a conflict of interest. However, both employers need the correct tax code to deduct the right amount of PAYE.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              Can I get a refund if too much tax was deducted from my second job?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">Yes. If the flat rate used on your secondary income results in more tax being deducted than you actually owe based on your total income, IRD will issue a refund as part of your automatic income tax assessment after the end of the tax year (31 March). You can also apply for a tailored (special) tax code from IRD to reduce over-deductions during the year.</p>
          </details>
        </div>

        <!-- Related Tools -->
        <div class="mt-10 border border-border rounded-xl p-6 bg-surface">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">Related Tools & Guides</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
            <li><a href="/" class="text-accent hover:underline">NZ Salary Calculator</a> - Calculate your primary income take home pay</li>
            <li><a href="/guides/tax-codes-nz/" class="text-accent hover:underline">NZ Tax Codes Explained</a> - Full reference for all primary and secondary tax codes</li>
            <li><a href="/guides/paye-tax-nz/" class="text-accent hover:underline">PAYE Tax in New Zealand</a> - How the progressive tax brackets work</li>
            <li><a href="/guides/student-loan-repayment-nz/" class="text-accent hover:underline">Student Loan Repayment</a> - Student loan deductions on secondary income</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Sources -->
        <div class="mt-8 border-t border-border pt-6">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-primary mb-3">Sources</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><a href="https://www.ird.govt.nz/income-tax/income-tax-for-individuals/tax-codes-and-tax-rates-for-individuals/secondary-tax-codes-and-rates" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">IRD - Secondary tax codes and rates</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.ird.govt.nz/income-tax/income-tax-for-individuals/tax-codes-and-tax-rates-for-individuals/work-out-your-tax-code" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">IRD - Work out your tax code</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.employment.govt.nz/hours-and-wages/pay/taxes-and-deductions/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">Employment New Zealand - Taxes and deductions</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
